A slap in the face and a mess of a movie. The film offered the writer/director a once-in-infinity opportunity to create the return of Luke Skywalker
column73: and we get... milking an alien? It was the ruination of Luke Skywalker. Can anyone really think this is the best they could do? Lucasfilm had to expect a vehemently negative reaction to Luke\'s storyline. This truly was an anti-Star Wars movie. The storylines for Fin and Poe were totally forgettable. They were useless digressions within digressions in which the characters seemingly fought to make themselves relevant to the movie. The casino was a royale flop. The CGI on that planet and in the fight scenes inside the First Order\'s ships looked unreal and were frequently inane. Vice Admiral Holdo? Lousy. Celeb cameos? In Star Wars? Seriously

Success and failure are at the forefront of 2017s newest entry to a saga from a Galaxy Far
column83: Far Away in Star Wars: The Last Jedi-sides to a coin that are deeply rooted in the franchise in both a thematic way (the Light/Dark Side) and a literal one as well (the Original Trilogy as a whole massive successes
column84: the Prequel Trilogy as a whole massive failures) -and what it means to succeed or fail at something and the gray in between. Writer/director Rian Johnson seems to understand these thematic elements that have lifted the collective imaginations of fans for decades by challenging what we know (or at least what we think we know)
column85: yet giving us a new lens to view them in satisfying and surprising ways and has also given us an excellent Star Wars film that can proudly confirm that the Sequel Trilogy are in good hands. The best looking Star Wars film made (to date)
